    "created_at": "2016-07-06T05:02:14Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-07-06T05:02:14Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> Regarding alt, if you're referring to the way it adds accents to characters on OS X, most people either rebind it to meta in the terminal, or use ESC.\n\nMost english almost-ascii-only user. And we likely don't have the same sample of terminal users.\nWe did adventure to some fancy keyboard in the past (agreed on notebook, so browser...), and we ended up preventing people from typing a minus (which is useful). And having spent quite some time with a mac french keyboard, I know for example that Alt is needed to type a pipe `|` (yes I know crazy) and this is typically the kind of things that make using a default emacs unusable on such a configuration.\n\n> I'm not sure if it was clear, but these are standard emacs keybindings.\n\nWe'll have to consider that it's also the default, and that's it's easier to bind an extra shortcut, that to unbind one.\n\nI'm not saying we should not, and despite the Emacs-like mode, it also have to stay close to a readline-like usage.\n\n> Most Linux terminals that I've used bind paste to something else, since C-v is used so often.\n\nThat's true, we would have to special case I guess.\n\nThough in previous IPython (due to readline?) C-v is \"insert literally next character\", which might be useful as well. So we should likely be careful. \n\nWith all these consideration I'm leaning toward :  \n- User who care can rebind [yes we need more docs and a simpler way].\n- User who will be annoyed have no clue how to deals with broken keybindings. \n\nA (maybe better?) solution would be to have more keymaps, a \"default\" one, which is limited and play it \"safe\", then the `emacs` and `vi` ones that are opt-in and more opinionated.\n"
  },
