    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I didn't expect this to be so controversial. On OS X, C-v and M-v literally just enter `^V` and `^[v`, or just beep the shell. But I guess OS X is implicitly more reasonable than other systems for terminal use because the OS level shortcuts don't use control. Alt-v enters `âˆš` with the default US English keyboard, by the way. \n\nIf you don't want to rebind C-v and M-v (though I still think you should, for emacs mode), maybe bind C-p and C-n to what page up/down currently do? That was the first thing I tried. \n\nAlternate thought: it seems that part of the issue here is that emacs mode is the default, but really you want the default to be \"reasonable\" mode, and have a separate \"emacs\" mode for emacs users, just like there's a \"vi\" mode for vi users. \n"
  },
